<br>
If you ask mages what they want with the fire pets, most will want either an old-style damage shield tank pet, or to have it be a more consistant caster.  That is, stop casting root, dispell, and AOEs, and instead focus on a mix of damage spells and stuns.  If it is supposed to be a caster, we would also like it to <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">act</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> like a caster, and stand at a distance from the enemy and cast.  Since a casting, wizard-like pet, is obvious a damage dealer, we would like it to do comparable damage to our other pets.  This means it should have a reasonable mix of damage dealing spells, and these spells should stick often enough to be worth while.<br>
<br>
No mage ever asked for fire pets to cast Ice Comet, and the notion of a fire pet casting cold spells is frankly ridiculous.<br>
<br>
What we do want is an actually useful pet, instead of the piece of garbage we have now.<br>
<br>
Do not confuse what Sony does for what mages want.  Sony resembles the famous <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Monkey's Paw</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> when it comes to fixes and upgrade.<br>
<br>
If you are going to read the Mage forum, I suggest you do so in detail, and do not simple paste the most incindiary quote you can find out of context in an attempt to smear mages.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Razamatazz Pizzazz</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Moderator, Mage Compendium</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Now for some specific responses.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Daamij:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  I see why Mages are so happy though.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->No.  Mages are neither happy about the post-50 fire pets as they are, nor is the proposed change what mages want either.  We do not want a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;signature spell&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> from wizards.<br>
<br>
What we want is a useful fire pet, ideally one that basically casts stuns and damage spells.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Zuratuli:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  130dps from a PET is ridiculous<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->That <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">is</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> ridiculous.  However, I think it is reasonable to look for 75-90 DPS from what ought to be a damage dealing pet, but which is a joke right now.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Edano:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  50+ mage pets have been wizards since Kunark. The only difference is that they may become a good wizard rather than a bad one.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Don't you mean <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">awful</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->?<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Zuratali:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Obviously this upgrade is powerful or else you would not waste your time arguing for it...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Mages are not arguing in favor of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Ice Comet</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> for fire elementals.  Read the posts more carefully.  What some mages are arguing is that since <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Sony</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is proposing to do so, it is not as awful as some make it out to be.  I disagree, I think it is a bad idea, but one need to examine what <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Sony</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is proposing.<br>
<br>
Blame <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Sony</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, not mages.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Zmabik:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  If we get our gate or root resisted/interrupted we can die just as quick. Our only escape mechanism is rooting and running, or gating, and like I said, if we can't get either off we die as well. (We could port but gating is faster)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Snare</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> effectively multiplies both the distance between you and the mob and the difference in run speed between you and the mob.  Thus, a snared mob is <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">much</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> easier to escape from.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Kinelaria:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  - Can't choose what spells it uses. It just follows a set script and tends to be unpredictable. It might chain cast nukes, it might chain cast snares or roots, you just never know what them crazy elementals will do.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->And this is where most mages would prefer changes.  Give it a smaller but more reliable spell set, and remove the problem spells.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Kinelaria:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  The bulk of the arguments I've seen here sum up to: it uses our coolest looking nuke, that is sooooo unfair.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Actually that is the only thing about this idea that tempts me in the least.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Ice Comet</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">so</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> cool when it lands.  But a fire elemental casting cold spells?  Don't seem right....<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>AvgWiz:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  1) It should get the naked hitpoints of a wizard of that level. 3900 hitpoints is WAY too high for a wizard of that level. It should have the melee skills of a wizard too.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->All other summoned pets have hitpoints comparage to a moderately equipped player of the same level as the pet.  However, they all have poor damage mitigation, except insofar as stun helps.  Further, if you actually read the thread, you'll find that 3900 HP is suggested by one mage that wants a <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">tanking</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> fire pet, like our old style ones, with a nice damage shield.  Please read carefully.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>AvgWiz:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  2) When summoned, it should come into the world without any mana. When wizards get rezzed, they have no mana either. Also, if pet get suspended -- it does not med. Let it med up for a while before it is useable. None of this re-claim energy re-summon tactics to get mana back for the pet.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->The whole point of elementals is the ability to summon a working non-player character.  My melee pets do not suffer from rez effects when summoned, why should my caster pet?<br>
<br>
Indeed, your other points are nothing more than naked hostility towards mages, and not worth replying in detail.  I suggest that you play alongside a mage in order to gain a more informed perspective on the class.<br>
<br>
The only legitimate concern in your post is regarding mage's avoiding the limited mana pool by reclaiming and recasting the fire pet.  This absolutely <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">does</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> need to be considered.  Since there is little to be gained by buffing or equipping a casting fire pet, there is little reason <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">not</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> to reclaim and recast it.  Therefore, it should be limited more by its spell set and less by its mana pool, which can be circumvented.<br>
<br>
Making the pet <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;med to full&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> upon summoning is inconsistant with the way elementals have always worked.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Quineloe:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Where do you live? a mob will NEVER chose a NPC over a PC in its melee range, your pet will NEVER get agro and get killed unless you cant control it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->A common belief, but simply not true.  If you read the beastlord forums, you would know that when two lords and two warders melee a mob, the mob consistantly aggroes onto the warder, not the lord, even though there are <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">two</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> player melees within combat range.  I have also seen this when multiple air pets outnumber player monks in melee range.<br>
<br>
As a result, beastlords currently theorize that the real aggro rule is something like <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;if the top of the hate list is a pet, attack the next highest within melee range, pet or not.&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  Thus, if pets occupy the first two spots on the hate list and within melee range, they will take aggro even in the presence of a player melee within combat distance.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Natan:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  It's hillarious for me to see Mages coming here and call us whiners, where the Mage community is and was for 3 years a whine festival.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->That is not what I read, and I moderate the mage forums closely.  Every class has its share of whiners.<br>
<br>
What I do see in this thread is far too many posters who do not read the threads carefully, take quotes and information out of context, and add to the confusion by exaggerating, distorting, and incitement.<br>
<br>
There being far more wizards than mages, there are of course far more wizard whiners, but one cannot conclude from that that wizards are generally whiners.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Rombus:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  I see no legitimate reason not to allow their pets to cast L39 concussion to lower their aggro.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->While that is certainly the most thematicly consistant way to add <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Concussion</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to the magician's pallette, i.e., through a pet cast like root and stun, it would involve modifying how aggro works.  As it stands now, a pet casting <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Concussion</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> would lower <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">its</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> position on the hate list, and <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">not</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> its master's hate.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Cyricus:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Seriously, read the Mage posts please - noone really cares if it´s Ice Comet or something else wich is doing similiar damage as long as the improved pet is doing around the same damage as the other three.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Exactly.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>TraigosOde:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  I believe I have already suggested that the spell summon an oom pet in this very thread. Try again.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Every elemental I have ever summoned has been ready to fight, and has never suffered from any form of rezz effects.  It has is a significant attribute of elementals that they are summoned ready-to-fight.  There is no reason to alter this for wizard pets.<br>
<br>
However, it does mean that a limited mana pool is not a significant limitation on a casting fire pet, since it can be easily overcome.  Instead, damage outpout should be limited by the mix of spells.<br>
<br>
In that context, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Ice Comet</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> clearly does not belong in the fire elemental's repetoire.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Jaytee:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Third, the pet should never ever ever melee anything. It is a wizard. It should never try and swing at anything. I would go so far as to think it should be rooted in place where summoned.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Yes.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Natan:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Unlimited mana pool is overpowering too.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Not if the spell mix is toned down.  If it cast smaller nukes that stick with some frequency, and its DPS is consistant with our other damage dealing pets, then what is the problem?<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Jaytee:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  You folks keep missing the point that if the pet does not do DPS similar to or exceeding our melee pets, there is no point using the pet. Which is the situation we have had with fire pets since Kunark was released.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Again, correct.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Natan:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Might be, but then give up some of your nuking power, else you will be overpowered and we will underpowered in relation to mages, if that thing goes life it it's current form.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Does not follow logically.  If asking for a damage dealing fire pet that deals damage comparable to our existing pets is overpowering, then mages must already be overpowered.<br>
<br>
Is that what you are arguing?<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Gebbly:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  What if the &quot;fire&quot; elemental pet got a fire-based DD instead?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Seems entirely reasonable for a fire elemental.  It would be nice if it also had a magic nuke on its list as well, but a fire elemental really ought to cast fire spells, and ought to do little damage against fire immune foes.<br>
<br>
The only disadvantage of modelling the fire elemental after a mage instead of a wizard is that stuns are one of the few uses of it as it exists now, and we would hate to lose that.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Natan:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  i think Mages overestimate snare and root anyway grossly.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->On the other hand, I think wizards grossly underestimate snare and root.  The lynchpin around which mages are balanced is that all their defense is focused in their pets.  No pet means no defense except fleeing, and mages have no spells other than gate that aid fleeing.  Besides chain casting a pet, magicians have no way to cope with adds.  If their pet is already engaged with an add and cannot be disengaged, the mage has no way to cope with adds.<br>
<br>
Snare has the effect of multiplying the distance between the mob and the player, thereby amplifying any speed advantage.<br>
<br>
Root is commonly known as <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;ghetto mez&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and is a powerful ability.<br>
<br>
These abilities are so useful, I often partner with a junior caster with those spells.  It makes things <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">so</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> much safer than I can accomplish on my own.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Natan:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  If you want to have it cast Wiz spells, limit it to level 44 max wiz spells. We have great spells at that level too, Conflag etc, Force Strike, Lightning Shock, Ice Shock, etc.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I do not know the wizard spell line well enough to have an informed opinion on this, except to say that a casting fire pet needs to be limited by the spells it casts and not its mana pool.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Natan:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Give it (Wiz) spells up to level 44 MAX, and make it immune to AEs, make it cast most of the time, so it becomes an additional and reasonable force in raids.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->This seems a reasonable solution.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Gebbly:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Surely it is better to discuss a change whilst it is on the test server so that when it is implemented it is to everyones satisfaction rather than waiting until it is on the prod servers when changing it would be a nuisance.<br>
<br>
If everyone stayed calm a lot more constructive criticism would be found.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Especially since there is likely to be more discussion than actual testing.<br>
<br>
